RRP with and without NAâ€™s

We consider both the cases with and without Not Applicableâ€™s in this document. First, we create an indicator for all RRP

RRP_set <- names(raw_data[86:107])[c(1, 2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 15, 16, 17, 19, 21 )]

Descriptives and plots

Overall

First, we calculate the descriptive statistics of the data with Not Applicableâ€™s

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #RRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(all_of(RRP_set)) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = FALSE) %>% #no missings
  describe() %>% .[, 2:5] %>% 
  print.data.frame()
##       n     mean       sd   median
## X1 6813 4.581562 1.163845 4.727273

Second, we print the means and SDâ€™s for the data without the rows that contain Not Applicableâ€™s.

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #RRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(all_of(RRP_set)) %>% 
  na_if(0) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = FALSE) %>% #i.e. listwise deletion of incomplete rows
  describe() %>% .[, 2:5] %>% 
  print.data.frame()
##       n     mean        sd   median
## X1 1893 5.459204 0.7196349 5.545455

Third, we consider the means and SDâ€™s for the RRPâ€™s for the data without the rows that contain Not Applicableâ€™s where for each row the mean is calculated based on the observed (i.e.Â applicable) values.

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #RRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(all_of(RRP_set)) %>% 
  na_if(0) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = TRUE) %>% #i.e. casewise deletion of unobserved values in row
  describe() %>% .[, 2:5] %>% 
  print.data.frame()
##       n     mean        sd median
## X1 6774 5.556312 0.7503754    5.6

By disciplinary field

First, we calculate the descriptive statistics of the data with Not Applicableâ€™s

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #RRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(D2, all_of(RRP_set)) %>% 
  mutate(rowM = rowMeans(select(., all_of(RRP_set)), na.rm = FALSE)) %>% 
  select(D2, rowM) %>% 
  melt(id.vars = "D2", value.name = "RRP_mean") %>% 
  group_by(D2) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), 
            mean = mean(RRP_mean, na.rm=TRUE), 
            sd = sd(RRP_mean, na.rm = TRUE))  %T>%    
  print.data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = D2, y = mean, 
             ymin = mean - 1.96*sd, 
             ymax = mean + 1.96*sd)) + 
  geom_pointrange(aes(group = D2, colour = D2), 
                  position = position_dodge(width = 1)) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks = element_blank())
##                                 D2 count     mean       sd
## 1   Social and Behavioral Sciences  1965 4.516771 1.157085
## 2              Arts and Humanities   636 3.868353 1.309557
## 3 Engineering and Natural Sciences  1465 4.634130 1.136992
## 4     Biomedical and Life Sciences  2747 4.765000 1.077444

By institutional support

First, we calculate the descriptive statistics of the data with Not Applicableâ€™s

mice::complete(imp, 1) %>% #RRP has no missings -so use 1st imputed set
  select(Group, all_of(RRP_set)) %>% 
  mutate(rowM = rowMeans(select(., all_of(RRP_set)), na.rm = FALSE)) %>% 
  select(Group, rowM) %>% 
  melt(id.vars = "Group", value.name = "RRP_mean") %>% 
  group_by(Group) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), 
            mean = mean(RRP_mean, na.rm=TRUE), 
            sd = sd(RRP_mean, na.rm = TRUE))  %T>%

  ggplot(aes(x = Group, y = mean, 
             ymin = mean - 1.96*sd, 
             ymax = mean + 1.96*sd)) +
